          "text": "<teammate-message teammate_id=\"team-lead\">\nYou are implementing Unit 6: Client migration from CompositeTransport to TransportCoordinator.\n\n## Task\n\nRewrite transport construction in `apps/client/src/tui/app.rs` to use `TransportCoordinator` instead of `CompositeTransport`. This is the biggest refactor in the mDNS discovery plan — it's what enables the coordinator's runtime target management (add/remove peers) to work with the client.\n\n## What Needs to Change\n\n### 1. Replace CompositeTransport with TransportCoordinator\n\nIn `apps/client/src/tui/app.rs`, the current code (around line 544-588):\n```rust\nlet mut composite = CompositeTransport::new();\nif let Some(ref http) = http_pool {\n    composite = composite.with_arc_transport(http.clone());\n}\nif let Some(mqtt) = mqtt_transport {\n    composite = composite.with_transport(mqtt);\n}\n// ... direct peers added to composite ...\nlet transport = Arc::new(composite);\nlet client = Client::new(identity, transport.clone(), ...);\n```\n\nShould become:\n```rust\nlet mut coordinator = TransportCoordinator::with_defaults();\nif let Some(http) = http_pool {\n    coordinator.set_http_pool(http);  // http_pool is already TransportPool<HttpTarget>\n}\n#[cfg(feature = \"mqtt\")]\nif let Some(mqtt_pool) = mqtt_pool {\n    coordinator.set_mqtt_pool(mqtt_pool);\n}\n// Direct peers: add as ephemeral targets to the HTTP pool\n// (the pool must exist — create one if only direct peers are configured)\nlet coordinator = Arc::new(coordinator);\n```\n\n### 2. Change Client type\n\n`Client<CompositeTransport>` → `Client<TransportCoordinator>`\n\nThe `Client` is generic over `T: Transport`. `TransportCoordinator` already implements `Transport`, so this is a type change.\n\n### 3. Handle direct_peers\n\nCurrently direct peers are added to `CompositeTransport` individually. With the coordinator, they should be added to the HTTP pool as ephemeral targets:\n\n```rust\nfor peer in &config.direct_peers {\n    let target_config = HttpTargetConfig::ephemeral(&peer.address)\n        .with_label(peer.name.as_deref().unwrap_or(&peer.address));\n    match HttpTarget::new(target_config) {\n        Ok(target) => {\n            coordinator.add_http_target(target);\n            // ...\n        }\n        Err(e) => { /* warn and skip */ }\n    }\n}\n```\n\nBut note: `add_http_target` requires the coordinator to have an HTTP pool. If only direct peers are configured (no HTTP nodes), you need to create an empty pool first:\n```rust\nif coordinator.http_pool().is_none() && !config.direct_peers.is_empty() {\n    coordinator.set_http_pool(TransportPool::new());\n}\n```\n\nWait — `coordinator` is behind `Arc` at this point. The mutation methods take `&self` so this works. But `set_http_pool` takes `&mut self`. So set up the pool BEFORE wrapping in Arc.\n\n### 4. Update TransportRegistry\n\nThe registry currently uses `TransportRegistry::with_composite(transport.clone())`. Update to use coordinator-based construction. The registry has a `TransportQuery` impl that the coordinator also implements, so you may be able to pass the coordinator directly or adapt.\n\n### 5. Update message receiving\n\nCurrently uses `MessageReceiver::new(http_pool)`. The coordinator has its own `subscribe()` method that does the same thing. Switch to:\n```rust\nlet (events, coordinator_handle) = coordinator.subscribe(our_routing_key);\n```\n\n### 6. Keep send_text_tiered() working\n\nThe client's outbox uses `send_text_tiered()` which calls `coordinator.submit_tiered()`. This should work automatically since `TransportCoordinator` already implements this.\n\n## Key Files to Modify\n\n- `apps/client/src/tui/app.rs` — main transport construction and wiring (this is the big one)\n- Possibly `apps/client/src/config.rs` if config types need updating\n\n## Important Constraints\n\n- Do NOT change any crate code (reme-transport, reme-core, etc.) — only the client app\n- The `Client<T: Transport>` generic should just work with