t's from `reme_message`. It should already be in scope. If not, add the import.\n\n- [ ] **Step 2: Create `process_message_local` method**\n\nAdd a new method to `impl<T: Transport> Client<T>` (the generic impl block, NOT the `TransportCoordinator` one — this method doesn't use transport). The method contains ALL the logic from the current `process_message` EXCEPT the tombstone send (lines 712-742).\n\n```rust\n/// Process an incoming envelope locally: decrypt, verify, store, update DAG.\n///\n/// This performs all local operations (crypto, storage, DAG tracking) without\n/// any network I/O. The caller is responsible for sending the tombstone\n/// returned in `ProcessedMessage::pending_tombstone`.\n///\n/// This split allows UIs to display the message immediately while the\n/// tombstone send happens asynchronously (fire-and-forget).\npub fn process_message_local(\n    &self,\n    outer: &OuterEnvelope,\n) -> Result<ProcessedMessage, ClientError> {\n```\n\nCopy the body of `process_message` from line 638 (routing key check) through to the end (line 876, `Ok(ReceivedMessage { ... })`), but:\n\n1. **Remove** the tombstone send block (lines 712-742: the `if should_tombstone { ... submit_ack_tombstone ... }` block)\n2. **Instead**, build the tombstone and include it in the return value:\n\n```rust\n    // Build tombstone for caller to send asynchronously (fire-and-forget)\n    let pending_tombstone = if should_tombstone {\n        Some(SignedAckTombstone::new(\n            outer.message_id,\n            ack_secret,\n            &self.private_key(),\n        ))\n    } else {\n        None\n    };\n```\n\n3. **Return** `ProcessedMessage` instead of `ReceivedMessage`:\n\n```rust\n    Ok(ProcessedMessage {\n        received: ReceivedMessage {\n            message_id: outer.message_id,\n            from: inner.from,\n            content: inner.content,\n            created_at_ms: inner.created_at_ms,\n            content_id,\n            has_gaps,\n            sender_state_